WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

2
00:01:04.023 --> 00:01:06.858
Everybody. heads up. Keep it clear. now.

3
00:01:06.943 --> 00:01:08.318
Keep it clear.

4
00:01:09.570 --> 00:01:11.195
Stand back.

5
00:01:23.292 --> 00:01:24.537
Slow it down.

6
00:01:35.054 --> 00:01:37.426
- Pushing team. move in there.
- Move in.

7
00:01:38.474 --> 00:01:41.391
- On your ready.
- I want tasers on full charge.

8
00:01:43.103 --> 00:01:46.270
Steady! Go on. Step back in.

9
00:01:46.690 --> 00:01:48.232
Ready. Move it.

10
00:01:49.568 --> 00:01:50.897
And push!

11
00:01:57.576 --> 00:02:00.363
Well. locked. Loading team. step away.

12
00:02:09.171 --> 00:02:11.210
Jophery. raise the gate.

13
00:02:29.024 --> 00:02:31.597
Block the opening! Don't let her get out!

14
00:02:40.994 --> 00:02:42.488
Somebody help him!

15
00:02:42.746 --> 00:02:44.573
Work her back!

16
00:02:56.051 --> 00:02:57.130
Shoot her!

17
00:02:59.179 --> 00:03:00.673
Shoot her!

18
00:03:35.965 --> 00:03:39.299
- I heard that Hammond's not even here.
- He sends his apologies.

19
00:03:39.385 --> 00:03:42.470
There's a $20 million lawsuit
for that worker's death...

20
00:03:42.555 --> 00:03:45.128
...and you're telling me
that Hammond can't see me?

21
00:03:45.224 --> 00:03:48.344
He had to leave early.
his daughter's getting a divorce.

22
00:03:48.436 --> 00:03:51.472
I understand. but we need to deal
with the situation now.

23
00:03:51.564 --> 00:03:53.722
- The insurance company...
- You okay?

24
00:03:56.277 --> 00:04:00.773
The underwriters feel that the accident's
raised safety questions about the park.

25
00:04:01.324 --> 00:04:03.447
That makes the investors very anxious.

26
00:04:03.534 --> 00:04:07.117
I had to promise to conduct
a thorough. on-site inspection.

27
00:04:08.706 --> 00:04:11.375
Hammond hates inspections.
They slow everything down.

28
00:04:11.459 --> 00:04:14.543
They'll pull the funding.
That'll slow him down even more.

29
00:04:20.718 --> 00:04:22.046
Watch your head.

30
00:04:22.553 --> 00:04:27.595
If two experts sign off on the island.
the insurance guys'll back off.

31
00:04:27.975 --> 00:04:31.011
I've already got Ian Malcolm.
but they think he's too trendy.

32
00:04:31.103 --> 00:04:32.681
- They want Alan Grant.
- Grant?

33
00:04:32.772 --> 00:04:34.930
You'll never get him out of Montana.

34
00:04:35.524 --> 00:04:36.520
Why not?

35
00:04:38.903 --> 00:04:39.982
Why not?

36
00:04:42.531 --> 00:04:44.524
Because Grant's like me.

37
00:04:46.410 --> 00:04:47.821
He's a digger.

38
00:05:32.539 --> 00:05:35.410
Dr. Grant. Dr. Sattler.
we're ready to try again.

39
00:05:36.710 --> 00:05:38.287
I hate computers.

40
00:05:38.670 --> 00:05:40.248
The feeling's mutual.

41
00:05:55.228 --> 00:05:56.426
Take a look.

42
00:05:59.357 --> 00:06:00.555
Did it work?

43
00:06:00.650 --> 00:06:03.735
- How long does this take?
- Should bring an immediate return.

44
00:06:03.820 --> 00:06:07.900
You shoot the radar into the ground.
and the bone bounces the image back.

45
00:06:08.575 --> 00:06:10.069
Bounces it back...

46
00:06:12.162 --> 00:06:14.201
This new program is incredible.

47
00:06:14.748 --> 00:06:18.247
A few more years' development.
and we won't even have to dig anymore.

48
00:06:18.334 --> 00:06:20.042
Where's the fun in that?

49
00:06:20.628 --> 00:06:24.128
It's a little distorted.
but I don't think it's the computer.

50
00:06:25.133 --> 00:06:28.336
Post-mortem contraction
of the posterior neck ligaments.

51
00:06:28.887 --> 00:06:29.966
Velociraptor?

52
00:06:30.054 --> 00:06:31.632
Yes. Good shape. too.

53
00:06:32.015 --> 00:06:35.134
It's 5. 6 feet high. I'm guessing 9 feet long.

54
00:06:35.226 --> 00:06:36.555
- Look...
- What'd you do?

55
00:06:36.644 --> 00:06:37.676
He touched it.

56
00:06:38.062 --> 00:06:42.012
- Dr. Grant's not machine compatible.
- Hell. they've got it in for me.

57
00:06:42.984 --> 00:06:45.605
And look at the half-moon shaped bones
in the wrist.

58
00:06:45.695 --> 00:06:48.150
It's no wonder these guys learned
how to fly.

59
00:06:50.199 --> 00:06:51.397
No. seriously.

60
00:06:53.661 --> 00:06:58.038
Maybe dinosaurs have more in common
with present-day birds than with reptiles.

61
00:06:58.583 --> 00:07:01.868
Look at the pubic bone. turned backward.
like a bird's.

62
00:07:01.961 --> 00:07:05.828
Look at the vertebrae.
full of air sacs and hollows. like a bird's.

63
00:07:06.549 --> 00:07:09.336
And even the word "raptor"
means "bird of prey. "

64
00:07:09.677 --> 00:07:11.634
That doesn't look very scary.

65
00:07:14.140 --> 00:07:16.049
More like a 6-foot turkey.

66
00:07:18.769 --> 00:07:19.849
A turkey?

67
00:07:22.148 --> 00:07:25.433
- Imagine yourself in the Cretaceous period.
- Here we go.

68
00:07:26.318 --> 00:07:30.482
You'd get yourfirst look at this
6- foot turkey as you enter a clearing.

69
00:07:30.614 --> 00:07:33.366
He moves like a bird.
lightly bobbing his head.

70
00:07:33.868 --> 00:07:38.079
You keep still because maybe
his visual acuity is based on movement...

71
00:07:38.164 --> 00:07:40.951
...like T. Rex and he'll lose you
if you don't move.

72
00:07:41.041 --> 00:07:43.248
But no. not Velociraptor.

73
00:07:43.878 --> 00:07:47.578
You stare at him
and he just stares right back.

74
00:07:48.507 --> 00:07:52.884
And that's when the attack comes.
Not from the front. but from the side.

75
00:07:53.679 --> 00:07:57.262
From the other two Raptors
you didn't even know were there.

76
00:07:58.851 --> 00:08:03.429
Because Velociraptor's a pack hunter.
He uses co-ordinated attack patterns...

77
00:08:03.939 --> 00:08:06.015
...and he is out in force today.

78
00:08:07.192 --> 00:08:09.315
And he slashes at you with this...

79
00:08:10.237 --> 00:08:14.317
...a 6-inch retractable claw.
like a razor. on the middle toe.

80
00:08:14.533 --> 00:08:18.447
He doesn't bother to bite your jugular
like a lion. No.

81
00:08:18.829 --> 00:08:20.371
He slashes at you...

82
00:08:21.248 --> 00:08:23.241
...here or here...

83
00:08:23.417 --> 00:08:24.448
Alan.

84
00:08:25.335 --> 00:08:29.119
Or maybe across the belly.
spilling your intestines.

85
00:08:30.382 --> 00:08:35.210
The point is. you are alive
when they start to eat you.

86
00:08:36.972 --> 00:08:39.973
So. you know. try to show a little respect.

87
00:08:41.143 --> 00:08:42.056
Okay.

88
00:08:50.026 --> 00:08:54.071
Alan. if you wanted to scare the kid.
you could've pulled a gun on him.

89
00:08:54.698 --> 00:08:56.690
Yeah. I know. Kids.

90
00:08:57.909 --> 00:08:59.902
You want to have one of those?

91
00:09:00.078 --> 00:09:04.954
I don't want that kid.
but a breed of child could be intriguing.

92
00:09:05.750 --> 00:09:07.708
I mean. what's so wrong with kids?

93
00:09:07.794 --> 00:09:12.123
They're noisy. they're messy.
they're expensive.

94
00:09:12.299 --> 00:09:13.627
Cheap. cheap.

95
00:09:13.883 --> 00:09:15.081
They smell.

96
00:09:15.510 --> 00:09:17.052
- They don't smell!
- Some smell.

97
00:09:17.137 --> 00:09:19.425
- Give me a break!
- Babies smell.

98
00:09:27.021 --> 00:09:29.061
- Cover the site!
- Cover up the dig!

99
00:09:29.149 --> 00:09:31.437
- Tell them to shut down!
- Cut the machine!

100
00:09:32.068 --> 00:09:34.393
Cover it all up. Pull it over.

101
00:09:36.239 --> 00:09:39.822
Just cut it. will you? Shut it down!

102
00:09:40.493 --> 00:09:41.524
What?

103
00:09:56.259 --> 00:09:59.094
What the hell do you think
you're doing in here?

104
00:09:59.762 --> 00:10:01.671
We were saving that.

105
00:10:02.557 --> 00:10:04.680
For today. I guarantee it.

106
00:10:06.310 --> 00:10:09.264
- Who in God's name do you think you are?
- John Hammond.

107
00:10:09.355 --> 00:10:12.724
And I'm delighted to meet you finally
in person. Dr. Grant.

108
00:10:13.943 --> 00:10:18.771
So. I can see that my $50.000 a year
has been well spent.

109
00:10:19.490 --> 00:10:20.688
Who's the jerk?

110
00:10:20.783 --> 00:10:24.199
- This is our paleobotanist. Dr...
- Sattler.

111
00:10:24.495 --> 00:10:26.571
Ellie. this is Mr. Hammond.

112
00:10:27.123 --> 00:10:30.040
I'm sorry about the dramatic entrance.
Dr. Sattler. but...

113
00:10:30.126 --> 00:10:32.118
- Did I say "jerk"?
... we're in a hurry.

114
00:10:32.211 --> 00:10:35.580
Will you have a drink?
We won't let it get warm. Sit down.

115
00:10:36.298 --> 00:10:39.549
- Let me have this.
- I'll just get a glass or two. I can do it.

116
00:10:39.635 --> 00:10:42.921
- There's samples all over here.
- I know my way around the kitchen.

117
00:10:43.013 --> 00:10:44.923
Now. I'll get right to the point.

118
00:10:46.642 --> 00:10:48.967
I like you. Both of you.

119
00:10:49.395 --> 00:10:52.645
I can tell instantly about people. It's a gift.

120
00:10:55.901 --> 00:10:58.902
I own an island off the coast of Costa Rica.

121
00:10:59.571 --> 00:11:02.987
I've leased it from the government
and during the last five years...

122
00:11:03.075 --> 00:11:05.566
...I've been setting up a biological preserve.

123
00:11:05.661 --> 00:11:08.033
Really spectacular. Spared no expense.

124
00:11:08.122 --> 00:11:11.573
Make the one I've got down in Kenya
look like a petting zoo.

125
00:11:11.667 --> 00:11:15.830
And there's no doubt our attractions
will drive kids out of their minds.

126
00:11:16.171 --> 00:11:19.291
- And what are those?
- Small versions of adults. honey.

127
00:11:19.383 --> 00:11:21.340
And not just kids. everyone.

128
00:11:21.593 --> 00:11:26.884
We're opening next year. if the lawyers
don't kill me first. Do you like lawyers?

129
00:11:27.891 --> 00:11:30.726
- I don't really know any.
- Don't really know any.

130
00:11:31.061 --> 00:11:35.889
I do. and there's a particular one right now.
who represents my investors.

131
00:11:36.149 --> 00:11:38.984
Says that they insist on outside opinions.

132
00:11:39.069 --> 00:11:40.693
What kind of opinions?

133
00:11:40.821 --> 00:11:43.822
Well. your kind.
not to put too fine a point on it.

134
00:11:43.907 --> 00:11:47.987
Let's face it. in your particularfields.
you're the top minds.

135
00:11:48.328 --> 00:11:50.534
And if I could just persuade you...

136
00:11:50.997 --> 00:11:54.164
...to sign off on the park.
give it your endorsement...

137
00:11:54.251 --> 00:11:58.663
...maybe even pen a wee testimonial.
I could get back on schedule.

138
00:12:00.257 --> 00:12:03.875
- Why would they care what we think?
- What kind of park is this?

139
00:12:06.429 --> 00:12:08.137
It's right up your alley.

140
00:12:10.892 --> 00:12:14.261
Why don't you come down.
just the pair of you. for the weekend?

141
00:12:14.354 --> 00:12:17.521
I'd love to have an opinion
of a paleobotanist as well.

142
00:12:17.983 --> 00:12:20.474
I've got a jet standing by at Choteau.

143
00:12:22.445 --> 00:12:24.770
I'm sorry. This isn't possible.

144
00:12:25.615 --> 00:12:27.275
We just dug up a new skeleton...

145
00:12:27.367 --> 00:12:31.411
I'd compensate you
by fully funding your dig...

146
00:12:31.788 --> 00:12:34.540
- This is a very unusual time.
- The timing is...

147
00:12:34.624 --> 00:12:36.949
...for a further three years.

148
00:12:41.965 --> 00:12:43.340
Where's the plane?

149
00:12:44.801 --> 00:12:45.963
- Okay.
- Three years.

150
00:12:46.052 --> 00:12:47.083
Cheers.

151
00:13:29.553 --> 00:13:30.633
Dodgson!

152
00:13:39.021 --> 00:13:40.813
You shouldn't use my name.

153
00:13:41.816 --> 00:13:44.651
Dodgson. We've got Dodgson here.

154
00:13:45.778 --> 00:13:48.483
See. nobody cares. Nice hat.

155
00:13:49.114 --> 00:13:51.950
What're you trying to look like.
a secret agent?

156
00:13:52.243 --> 00:13:53.737
- Well?
- $750.000.

157
00:13:54.328 --> 00:13:56.784
On delivery. $50.000 more
for each viable embryo.

158
00:13:56.872 --> 00:13:59.909
That's $1.5 million
if you get all 15 species off the island.

159
00:14:00.084 --> 00:14:01.115
I'll get them all.

160
00:14:01.210 --> 00:14:05.124
Remember. viable embryos.
They're no use to us if they don't survive.

161
00:14:05.214 --> 00:14:07.456
How am I supposed to transport them?

162
00:14:11.220 --> 00:14:12.928
The bottom screws open.

163
00:14:14.348 --> 00:14:16.257
That's great. Oh. my God.

164
00:14:16.350 --> 00:14:18.888
It's cooled and compartmentalised inside.

165
00:14:19.103 --> 00:14:22.518
- You guys. That's great.
- Customs can even check it if they want to.

166
00:14:22.606 --> 00:14:23.981
- Let me see.
- Go on.

167
00:14:24.817 --> 00:14:27.734
- There's enough coolant for 36 hours.
- No menthol?

168
00:14:27.986 --> 00:14:31.071
The embryos have to be back here
in San José by then.

169
00:14:31.156 --> 00:14:32.900
That's up to your guy on the boat.

170
00:14:32.991 --> 00:14:36.656
7:00 tomorrow night on the east dock.
Make sure he gets it right.

171
00:14:36.787 --> 00:14:40.736
- How are you planning to beat security?
- I've got an 18-minute window.

172
00:14:40.916 --> 00:14:44.534
18 minutes and your company
catches up on 10 years of research.

173
00:14:48.924 --> 00:14:50.916
Don't get cheap on me. Dodgson.

174
00:14:53.470 --> 00:14:55.297
That was Hammond's mistake.

175
00:15:09.569 --> 00:15:12.356
So you two dig up dinosaurs?

176
00:15:14.658 --> 00:15:16.567
- Well...
- We try to.

177
00:15:22.916 --> 00:15:25.371
You'll have to get used to Dr. Malcolm.

178
00:15:25.627 --> 00:15:30.004
He suffers from a deplorable excess
of personality. for a mathematician.

179
00:15:30.090 --> 00:15:32.047
Chaotician. Chaotician. actually.

180
00:15:32.133 --> 00:15:33.925
John doesn't subscribe to chaos...

181
00:15:34.010 --> 00:15:36.797
...particularly what it says
about his science project.

182
00:15:36.888 --> 00:15:40.221
Ian. you've never been able to
sufficiently explain your concerns...

183
00:15:40.308 --> 00:15:43.179
Because of the behaviour
of the system in phase space?

184
00:15:43.269 --> 00:15:46.555
A load. if I may say so.
of fashionable number crunching...

185
00:15:46.773 --> 00:15:47.852
Don't.

186
00:15:47.982 --> 00:15:51.067
Dr. Sattler. Dr. Grant.
you've heard of Chaos Theory?

187
00:15:51.361 --> 00:15:52.274
No.

188
00:15:52.403 --> 00:15:54.195
No? Non-linear equations?

189
00:15:55.156 --> 00:15:56.650
Strange attractors?

190
00:15:58.660 --> 00:16:03.286
I refuse to believe that you aren't familiar
with the concept of attraction.

191
00:16:07.376 --> 00:16:10.662
I bring scientists. You bring a rock star.

192
00:16:15.134 --> 00:16:16.165
There it is.

193
00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:48.825
Bad wind shears. We have to drop
pretty fast. Hold on. this will be thrilling.

194
00:17:16.653 --> 00:17:19.323
But you need that piece over here.
and that piece...

195
00:17:19.406 --> 00:17:22.158
We'll have landed
by the time you get it right.

196
00:17:23.452 --> 00:17:24.650
Great.

197
00:18:42.655 --> 00:18:45.325
The full 50 miles of perimeterfence
are in place?

198
00:18:45.408 --> 00:18:48.611
And the concrete moats.
and the motion-sensor tracking systems.

199
00:18:48.703 --> 00:18:51.906
Donald. dear boy. relax.
Try and enjoy yourself.

200
00:18:52.165 --> 00:18:55.082
Let's get this straight.
This is not a weekend excursion.

201
00:18:55.168 --> 00:18:58.252
This is a serious investigation
of the stability of the island.

202
00:18:58.338 --> 00:19:01.457
Your investors. whom I represent.
are deeply concerned.

203
00:19:01.549 --> 00:19:04.799
48 hours from now.
if they're not convinced. I'm not convinced.

204
00:19:04.886 --> 00:19:06.629
I'll shut you down. John.

205
00:19:07.221 --> 00:19:11.385
In 48 hours.
I'll be accepting your apologies.

206
00:19:20.735 --> 00:19:23.023
All right. slow down. Slow. Stop.

207
00:19:25.239 --> 00:19:26.733
This shouldn't be here.

208
00:19:46.761 --> 00:19:49.596
Alan. this species of veriforman
has been extinct. since...

209
00:19:49.680 --> 00:19:52.432
...the Cretaceous Period.
I mean. this thing...

210
00:19:52.516 --> 00:19:53.845
What?

211
00:20:23.505 --> 00:20:24.750
Look at that.

212
00:20:28.135 --> 00:20:30.341
It's a dinosaur.

213
00:20:34.516 --> 00:20:37.850
You did it. Crazy son of a bitch. you did it.

214
00:20:39.188 --> 00:20:42.770
We could tear up the rule book
on cold-bloodedness. It doesn't apply.

215
00:20:42.858 --> 00:20:45.230
They're wrong.
This is a warm-blooded creature.

216
00:20:45.319 --> 00:20:49.019
- This thing doesn't live in a swamp.
- This thing's got a 25. 27-foot neck?

217
00:20:49.114 --> 00:20:51.652
- The Brachiosaurus? 30.
- 30 feet.

218
00:21:08.258 --> 00:21:10.796
We're gonna make a fortune
with this place.

219
00:21:15.724 --> 00:21:17.182
How fast are they?

220
00:21:17.309 --> 00:21:20.512
Well. we clocked the T. Rex
at 32 miles an hour.

221
00:21:22.397 --> 00:21:23.772
T. Rex?

222
00:21:24.899 --> 00:21:26.809
You said you've got a T. Rex?

223
00:21:27.986 --> 00:21:29.101
Say again.

224
00:21:30.155 --> 00:21:31.483
We have a T. Rex.

225
00:21:33.450 --> 00:21:35.608
Put your head between your knees.

226
00:21:36.036 --> 00:21:37.280
Dr. Grant...

227
00:21:37.746 --> 00:21:39.655
...my dear Dr. Sattler...

228
00:21:40.039 --> 00:21:43.871
...welcome to Jurassic Park.

229
00:22:06.899 --> 00:22:08.691
They're moving in herds.

230
00:22:10.945 --> 00:22:12.523
They do move in herds.

231
00:22:20.580 --> 00:22:22.204
How did you do this?

232
00:22:25.001 --> 00:22:26.329
I'll show you.

233
00:22:50.735 --> 00:22:52.442
G'day.

234
00:22:53.154 --> 00:22:56.736
The most advanced amusement park
in the entire world...

235
00:22:57.241 --> 00:22:59.779
...incorporating all the latest technologies.

236
00:22:59.869 --> 00:23:03.154
And I'm not talking just about rides.
Everybody has rides.

237
00:23:03.247 --> 00:23:07.458
No. we've made living
biological attractions so astounding...

238
00:23:07.626 --> 00:23:11.126
...that they'll capture the imagination
of the entire planet.

239
00:23:11.547 --> 00:23:13.290
So. what are you thinking?

240
00:23:14.591 --> 00:23:17.509
- That we're out of a job.
- Don't you mean "extinct"?

241
00:23:25.602 --> 00:23:29.600
Why don't you all sit down?
Donald. sit down.

242
00:23:30.482 --> 00:23:33.567
Here he comes. Well. here I come.

243
00:23:38.240 --> 00:23:39.236
<i>Hello.</i>

244
00:23:40.242 --> 00:23:41.405
Say hello.

245
00:23:41.660 --> 00:23:42.609
Hello.

246
00:23:43.996 --> 00:23:45.158
<i>Hello. John.</i>

247
00:23:45.872 --> 00:23:47.664
Yes. I've got lines.

248
00:23:47.749 --> 00:23:51.201
<i>Well. fine. I guess.
But. how did I get here?</i>

249
00:23:52.713 --> 00:23:56.212
Well. let me show you.
First. I'll need a drop of blood.

250
00:23:56.925 --> 00:23:58.040
Your blood.

251
00:23:58.135 --> 00:23:59.130
<i>Right.</i>

252
00:24:00.971 --> 00:24:02.169
<i>That hurt.</i>

253
00:24:02.639 --> 00:24:05.723
Relax. John.
It's all part of the miracle of cloning.

254
00:24:05.934 --> 00:24:07.843
<i>Hello. John.</i>

255
00:24:09.855 --> 00:24:13.935
Cloned from what? Loy extraction
hasn't recreated an intact DNA strand.

256
00:24:14.025 --> 00:24:16.101
Not without massive sequence gaps.

257
00:24:16.194 --> 00:24:18.021
Paleo DNA. from what source?

258
00:24:18.780 --> 00:24:22.196
Where do you get 100 million-year-old
dinosaur blood?

259
00:24:27.038 --> 00:24:28.236
<i>What? What?</i>

260
00:24:28.999 --> 00:24:31.953
<i>Well. Mr. DNA. where did you come from?</i>

261
00:24:32.127 --> 00:24:33.407
<i>From your blood.</i>

262
00:24:33.503 --> 00:24:37.797
<i>Just one drop of your blood
contains billions of strands of DNA...</i>

263
00:24:38.133 --> 00:24:40.374
<i>...the building blocks of life.</i>

264
00:24:41.136 --> 00:24:45.797
<i>A DNA strand like me
is a blueprint for building a living thing.</i>

265
00:24:46.015 --> 00:24:51.258
<i>And sometimes animals that went extinct
millions of years ago. like dinosaurs...</i>

266
00:24:51.521 --> 00:24:56.479
<i>...left their blueprints behind for us to find.
Wejust had to know where to look.</i>

267
00:24:56.651 --> 00:25:01.479
<i>100 million years ago.
there were mosquitoesjust like today.</i>

268
00:25:01.614 --> 00:25:04.900
<i>Andjust like today.
they fed on the blood of animals.</i>

269
00:25:05.201 --> 00:25:09.744
<i>Even dinosaurs.
Sometimes. after biting a dinosaur...</i>

270
00:25:10.081 --> 00:25:14.577
<i>...mosquitoes would land on the branch
of a tree and get stuck in the sap.</i>

271
00:25:14.919 --> 00:25:19.830
<i>After a long time. the tree sap
would get hard and become fossilised...</i>

272
00:25:19.966 --> 00:25:24.841
<i>...just like a dinosaur bone.
preserving the mosquito inside.</i>

273
00:25:25.555 --> 00:25:29.137
<i>This fossilised tree sap.
which we call amber...</i>

274
00:25:29.433 --> 00:25:33.727
<i>...waited for millions of years
with the mosquito inside...</i>

275
00:25:33.896 --> 00:25:36.897
<i>...until Jurassic Park scientists came along.</i>

276
00:25:37.817 --> 00:25:42.028
<i>Using sophisticated techniques.
they extract the preserved blood...</i>

277
00:25:42.113 --> 00:25:46.442
<i>...from the mosquito.
and bingo: dino DNA!</i>

278
00:25:47.576 --> 00:25:51.870
<i>A full DNA strand contains
three billion genetic codes.</i>

279
00:25:52.456 --> 00:25:56.584
<i>If we looked at screens like these
once a second for eight hours a day...</i>

280
00:25:56.669 --> 00:26:00.832
<i>...it'd take two years
to look at the entire DNA strand.</i>

281
00:26:00.923 --> 00:26:05.585
<i>It's that long.
Since it's so old. it's full of holes.</i>

282
00:26:06.220 --> 00:26:08.889
<i>Now that's where our geneticists
take over.</i>

283
00:26:09.431 --> 00:26:12.682
<i>Thinking machine super-computers
and gene sequencers...</i>

284
00:26:12.768 --> 00:26:15.176
<i>...break down the strand in minutes.</i>

285
00:26:15.396 --> 00:26:17.435
<i>And virtual-reality displays...</i>

286
00:26:17.523 --> 00:26:20.689
<i>...show our geneticists the gaps
in the DNA sequence.</i>

287
00:26:21.276 --> 00:26:23.767
<i>We used the complete DNA of a frog...</i>

288
00:26:23.862 --> 00:26:27.777
<i>...to fill in the holes and complete the code.</i>

289
00:26:28.367 --> 00:26:32.530
<i>Whew! And now.
we can make a baby dinosaur.</i>

290
00:26:35.707 --> 00:26:39.408
This score is only temporary.
It all has very dramatic music. of course.

291
00:26:40.337 --> 00:26:42.910
A march or something.
It hasn't been written yet.

292
00:26:43.006 --> 00:26:44.549
And then. the tour moves on.

293
00:26:54.393 --> 00:26:58.640
<i>Well. look here.
Those hard-working cowpokes...</i>

294
00:26:59.272 --> 00:27:01.645
This is overwhelming. John.

295
00:27:01.817 --> 00:27:05.814
Are these characters autoerotica?

296
00:27:05.946 --> 00:27:08.651
No. we have no animatronics here.

297
00:27:08.865 --> 00:27:11.985
Those people are the real miracle workers
of Jurassic Park.

298
00:27:12.285 --> 00:27:15.489
<i>...in unfertilised emu or ostrich eggs.</i>

299
00:27:16.289 --> 00:27:19.243
Wait a minute.
How do you interrupt the cellular mitosis?

300
00:27:19.334 --> 00:27:22.039
- Can't we see the unfertilised eggs?
- Shortly.

301
00:27:23.171 --> 00:27:27.085
<i>Now a whole team of genetic engineers
goes to work on...</i>

302
00:27:27.175 --> 00:27:30.544
- Can't you stop these things?
- I'm sorry. It's kind of a ride.

303
00:27:30.637 --> 00:27:32.594
One. two. three.

304
00:27:34.307 --> 00:27:35.636
You can't do that.

305
00:27:35.934 --> 00:27:37.973
- What?
- Can they do that?

306
00:27:40.522 --> 00:27:44.851
<i>A reminder: the boat for the mainland
will be leaving at 19:00.</i>

307
00:27:44.943 --> 00:27:49.854
<i>All personnel be at the dock
no later than 18:45. No exceptions.</i>

308
00:27:50.657 --> 00:27:53.860
- G'day. Henry.
- Good day. sir.

309
00:28:07.840 --> 00:28:09.418
It's turning the eggs.

310
00:28:13.012 --> 00:28:17.140
Perfect timing. I'd hoped they'd hatch
before I had to go to the boat.

311
00:28:17.225 --> 00:28:19.680
Henry. why didn't you tell me?

312
00:28:19.894 --> 00:28:23.808
I insist on being here when they're born.

313
00:28:24.565 --> 00:28:26.937
Come on.

314
00:28:28.486 --> 00:28:31.440
Come on. little one.

315
00:28:41.207 --> 00:28:43.034
Very good. Push.

316
00:28:45.002 --> 00:28:47.161
- Very good.
- God.

317
00:28:47.254 --> 00:28:49.662
Push. Come on.

318
00:28:50.257 --> 00:28:53.175
Come on. Come on. then.

319
00:28:53.469 --> 00:28:56.304
There you are. There.

320
00:29:01.352 --> 00:29:05.396
They imprint on the first creature
they come in contact with.

321
00:29:06.023 --> 00:29:07.731
Helps them to trust me.

322
00:29:08.067 --> 00:29:13.405
I've been present for the birth
of every creature on this island.

323
00:29:14.448 --> 00:29:17.651
Surely not the ones
that have bred in the wild.

324
00:29:17.826 --> 00:29:20.068
Actually they can't breed in the wild.

325
00:29:20.162 --> 00:29:22.997
Population control is one
of our security precautions.

326
00:29:23.082 --> 00:29:26.036
There's no unauthorised breeding
in Jurassic Park.

327
00:29:27.294 --> 00:29:29.453
How do you know they can't breed?

328
00:29:30.672 --> 00:29:34.041
Because all the animals
in Jurassic Park are female.

329
00:29:34.134 --> 00:29:36.506
We've engineered them that way.

330
00:29:36.678 --> 00:29:38.221
There you are.

331
00:29:40.516 --> 00:29:43.267
Oh. my God. Look at that.

332
00:29:43.685 --> 00:29:47.137
Blood temperature seems like
about high 80s. maybe.

333
00:29:47.231 --> 00:29:47.977
What?

334
00:29:48.065 --> 00:29:49.559
- 91.
- 91.

335
00:29:49.650 --> 00:29:51.891
Homeothermic? It holds that temperature?

336
00:29:51.985 --> 00:29:53.100
Yes.

337
00:29:57.699 --> 00:30:00.451
But. again. how do you know
they're all female?

338
00:30:00.535 --> 00:30:04.616
What. does somebody go out in the park
and pull up the dinosaurs' skirts?

339
00:30:04.706 --> 00:30:08.206
We control their chromosomes.
It's really not that difficult.

340
00:30:08.293 --> 00:30:10.701
All vertebrate embryos
are inherently female.

341
00:30:10.796 --> 00:30:14.628
They just require an extra hormone
given at the right developmental stage...

342
00:30:14.716 --> 00:30:15.831
...to make them male.

343
00:30:15.926 --> 00:30:18.843
- We simply deny them that.
- Deny them that?

344
00:30:18.929 --> 00:30:22.511
John. the kind of control
you're attempting is not possible.

345
00:30:22.599 --> 00:30:25.600
If there's one thing the history
of evolution has taught us...

346
00:30:25.685 --> 00:30:29.897
...it's that life will not be contained.
Life breaks free. Expands to new places...

347
00:30:30.190 --> 00:30:33.773
...and it crashes through barriers.
painfully. maybe even dangerously...

348
00:30:33.860 --> 00:30:36.565
...but there it is.

349
00:30:38.114 --> 00:30:39.573
There it is.

350
00:30:39.866 --> 00:30:45.073
You're implying that a group composed
entirely of female animals will breed.

351
00:30:45.163 --> 00:30:49.576
No. I'm simply saying that life finds a way.

352
00:30:56.758 --> 00:30:58.632
What species is this?

353
00:31:00.720 --> 00:31:02.345
It's a Velociraptor.

354
00:31:06.517 --> 00:31:08.012
You bred Raptors?

355
00:31:21.157 --> 00:31:26.400
Dr. Grant! As I was saying. we laid on
lunch for you before you go into the park.

356
00:31:26.496 --> 00:31:29.532
- Our gourmet chef. Alejandro...
- What are they doing?

357
00:31:35.838 --> 00:31:37.036
Feeding them.

358
00:31:42.094 --> 00:31:47.337
Alejandro's prepared a delightful menu
for us. Chilean sea bass.

359
00:31:48.267 --> 00:31:49.298
Shall we?

360
00:32:29.350 --> 00:32:31.638
They should all be destroyed.

361
00:32:31.727 --> 00:32:32.842
Robert Muldoon.

362
00:32:32.936 --> 00:32:34.728
My game warden from Kenya.

363
00:32:34.813 --> 00:32:37.814
Bit of an alarmist. but knows more
about Raptors than anyone.

364
00:32:37.900 --> 00:32:39.643
What's their growth rate?

365
00:32:39.735 --> 00:32:42.404
They're lethal at eight months.
and I do mean lethal.

366
00:32:42.488 --> 00:32:46.070
I've hunted most things that can hunt you.
but how these things move...

367
00:32:46.158 --> 00:32:48.150
- Fast for a biped?
- Cheetah speed.

368
00:32:48.243 --> 00:32:51.280
50. 60 miles per hour
if they ever got out in the open.

369
00:32:51.371 --> 00:32:53.163
And they're astonishing jumpers.

370
00:32:53.248 --> 00:32:56.498
Yes. That's why we're taking
extreme precautions.

371
00:32:57.920 --> 00:33:00.327
Do they show intelligence?

372
00:33:00.422 --> 00:33:04.123
They show extreme intelligence.
Even problem-solving intelligence.

373
00:33:04.760 --> 00:33:06.135
Especially the big one.

374
00:33:06.511 --> 00:33:08.800
We bred eight originally.
but when she came in...

375
00:33:08.889 --> 00:33:12.222
...she took over the pride
and killed all but two of the others.

376
00:33:12.309 --> 00:33:17.932
That one. when she looks at you.
you can see she's working things out.

377
00:33:19.357 --> 00:33:21.599
That's why we have to feed them like this.

378
00:33:21.693 --> 00:33:24.729
She had them all attacking the fences
when the feeders came.

379
00:33:24.821 --> 00:33:26.565
The fences are electrified. right?

380
00:33:26.656 --> 00:33:29.741
That's right. but they never attack
the same place twice.

381
00:33:29.951 --> 00:33:33.616
They were testing the fences
for weaknesses systematically.

382
00:33:35.040 --> 00:33:36.534
They remember.

383
00:33:47.802 --> 00:33:50.673
Yes. Well. who's hungry?

384
00:33:51.056 --> 00:33:54.674
<i>More adventurous guests. of course.
can opt for ourjungle river cruise...</i>

385
00:33:54.768 --> 00:33:56.974
<i>...or for a close-up look at our majestic...</i>

386
00:33:57.061 --> 00:34:00.561
None of these attractions are ready yet.
but the park will open...

387
00:34:00.648 --> 00:34:04.978
...with the basic tour you are about to take.
and then other rides will come on-line...

388
00:34:05.069 --> 00:34:08.688
...six or twelve months after that.
Absolutely spectacular designs.

389
00:34:08.781 --> 00:34:12.067
- Spared no expense.
- And we can charge anything we want.

390
00:34:12.160 --> 00:34:14.865
$2.000 a day. $10.000 a day.
and people will pay it.

391
00:34:14.954 --> 00:34:17.825
- And there's the merchandise...
- Donald.

392
00:34:18.333 --> 00:34:21.583
This park was not built to cater
only for the super rich.

393
00:34:21.669 --> 00:34:24.670
Everyone in the world has the right
to enjoy these animals.

394
00:34:24.756 --> 00:34:25.870
Sure. They will.

395
00:34:25.965 --> 00:34:29.416
We'll have a coupon day or something.

396
00:34:33.347 --> 00:34:39.101
The lack of humility before nature
that's being displayed here staggers me.

397
00:34:39.896 --> 00:34:43.395
I think things are a little different
than you and I had feared.

398
00:34:43.482 --> 00:34:45.060
I know. They're a lot worse.

399
00:34:45.151 --> 00:34:48.401
Now. wait a second.
we haven't even seen the park yet...

400
00:34:49.113 --> 00:34:53.407
Donald. let him talk. There's no reason.
I want to hear every viewpoint.

401
00:34:53.492 --> 00:34:57.953
Don't you see the danger. John.
inherent in what you're doing here?

402
00:34:58.247 --> 00:35:01.414
Genetic power's the most awesome force
the planet's ever seen...

403
00:35:01.500 --> 00:35:04.371
...but you wield it like a kid
that's found his dad's gun.

404
00:35:04.462 --> 00:35:07.961
- It's hardly appropriate to start hurling...
- Lf I may.

405
00:35:08.132 --> 00:35:11.797
I'll tell you the problem
with the scientific power you're using here.

406
00:35:11.886 --> 00:35:15.670
It didn't require any discipline to attain it.

407
00:35:16.056 --> 00:35:19.591
You read what others had done
and you took the next step.

408
00:35:19.727 --> 00:35:21.885
You didn't earn the knowledge
for yourselves...

409
00:35:21.979 --> 00:35:24.731
...so you don't take
any responsibility for it.

410
00:35:25.399 --> 00:35:29.563
You stood on the shoulders of geniuses to
accomplish something as fast as you could.

411
00:35:29.653 --> 00:35:33.733
Before you even knew what you had.
you patented it. and packaged it...

412
00:35:33.824 --> 00:35:38.071
...and slapped it on a plastic lunch box.
and now you're selling it.

413
00:35:39.413 --> 00:35:41.702
I don't think you're giving us
our due credit.

414
00:35:41.790 --> 00:35:45.206
Our scientists have done things
which nobody has ever done before.

415
00:35:45.294 --> 00:35:48.544
But your scientists were so preoccupied
with whether they could...

416
00:35:48.630 --> 00:35:50.872
...they didn't stop to think if they should.

417
00:35:50.966 --> 00:35:54.715
Condors.
Condors are on the verge of extinction.

418
00:35:54.928 --> 00:36:00.468
If I created condors on this island.
you wouldn't have anything to say.

419
00:36:00.559 --> 00:36:03.264
This isn't some species
that was obliterated...

420
00:36:03.353 --> 00:36:06.473
...by deforestation or the building of a dam.

421
00:36:06.815 --> 00:36:11.773
Dinosaurs had their shot
and nature selected them for extinction.

422
00:36:13.530 --> 00:36:17.777
I don't understand this Luddite attitude.
Especially from a scientist.

423
00:36:17.868 --> 00:36:22.779
How can we stand in the light of discovery
and not act?

424
00:36:22.873 --> 00:36:26.538
What's so great about discovery?
It's a violent. penetrative act...

425
00:36:26.626 --> 00:36:30.209
...that scars what it explores.
What you call discovery...

426
00:36:31.298 --> 00:36:34.002
...I call the rape of the natural world.

427
00:36:34.885 --> 00:36:38.882
The question is. how can you know
anything about an extinct eco-system?

428
00:36:38.972 --> 00:36:41.973
How could you ever assume
that you can control it?

429
00:36:42.058 --> 00:36:46.471
You have poisonous plants in this building.
You picked them because they look good.

430
00:36:46.563 --> 00:36:50.774
But these are aggressive living things
that have no idea what century they're in...

431
00:36:50.859 --> 00:36:53.860
...and they'll defend themselves.
Violently. if necessary.

432
00:36:56.281 --> 00:37:01.523
Dr. Grant. If there's one person who
could appreciate what I am trying to do...

433
00:37:03.121 --> 00:37:07.866
The world has just changed so radically
and we're all running to catch up.

434
00:37:08.585 --> 00:37:13.128
I don't want to jump to any conclusions.
but dinosaurs and man...

435
00:37:13.256 --> 00:37:17.419
...two species separated
by 65 million years of evolution...

436
00:37:17.510 --> 00:37:20.961
...have just been suddenly
thrown back into the mix together.

437
00:37:21.055 --> 00:37:25.433
How can we possibly have
the slightest idea what to expect?

438
00:37:26.561 --> 00:37:28.767
I don't believe it.

439
00:37:28.855 --> 00:37:32.140
You're meant to come here
and defend me against these characters...

440
00:37:32.233 --> 00:37:35.684
...and the only one I've got on my side
is the blood-sucking lawyer.

441
00:37:36.529 --> 00:37:37.692
Thank you.

442
00:37:44.745 --> 00:37:46.026
They're here.

443
00:37:46.831 --> 00:37:49.666
You four are gonna have a spot
of company out in the park.

444
00:37:49.750 --> 00:37:52.538
Spend a little time
with our target audience.

445
00:37:52.628 --> 00:37:53.707
Grandpa!

446
00:37:54.046 --> 00:37:55.209
Kids!

447
00:37:58.175 --> 00:38:01.675
- Wait! Careful with me.
- We missed you.

448
00:38:02.304 --> 00:38:06.005
- We loved the presents. They were great.
- Did you enjoy the helicopter?

449
00:38:06.100 --> 00:38:08.769
Yeah. it went down
and we all went right up.

450
00:38:12.064 --> 00:38:15.231
Now. kids. come away.
Not too close to the cars.

451
00:38:16.735 --> 00:38:19.772
Aren't they lovely?
Aren't they glorious. though.

452
00:38:19.864 --> 00:38:22.355
These will be your transports
for the afternoon.

453
00:38:22.449 --> 00:38:25.154
- No drivers?
- No. drivers. They're electric.

454
00:38:25.244 --> 00:38:28.280
They run on this track
in the middle of the roadway here.

455
00:38:28.372 --> 00:38:31.289
Totally non-polluting. Top of the line.
Spared no expense.

456
00:38:31.584 --> 00:38:34.157
It's an interactive CD-ROM!

457
00:38:34.253 --> 00:38:37.254
You touch the screen
and it talks about whatever you want.

458
00:38:37.339 --> 00:38:40.424
Lex. you're all right in there.
Dr. Sattler. come with me.

459
00:38:40.509 --> 00:38:42.418
Dr. Grant. come in the second car.

460
00:38:42.511 --> 00:38:45.084
I'm gonna ride with. Dr. Sattler.

461
00:38:56.650 --> 00:38:58.310
I read your book.

462
00:38:59.862 --> 00:39:01.107
That's great.

463
00:39:02.072 --> 00:39:05.737
Do you really think dinosaurs turned
into birds and that's where they went?

464
00:39:07.202 --> 00:39:10.073
A few species may have evolved
along those lines.

465
00:39:15.085 --> 00:39:17.457
They sure don't look like birds to me.

466
00:39:18.797 --> 00:39:21.632
I heard that there was this meteor...

467
00:39:21.800 --> 00:39:26.011
...hit the earth someplace down in Mexico
and made this big crater.

468
00:39:26.096 --> 00:39:27.424
Listen...

469
00:39:29.850 --> 00:39:32.519
...Tim. which car were you planning on?

470
00:39:33.937 --> 00:39:35.728
Whichever one you are.

471
00:39:38.400 --> 00:39:43.607
<i>I heard about this thing in Omni
about this meteor making all this heat.</i>

472
00:39:43.738 --> 00:39:46.229
It made diamond dust
and that changed the weather.

473
00:39:46.324 --> 00:39:47.949
They died because of the weather.

474
00:39:48.034 --> 00:39:52.495
My teacher tells me about this book
by a guy named Bakker. He says...

475
00:39:54.457 --> 00:39:57.909
She said I should ride with you
'cause it'd be good for you.

476
00:39:58.336 --> 00:40:00.044
<i>The boat is now loading.</i>

477
00:40:00.130 --> 00:40:04.838
<i>Everyone must be on the dock
for the 19:00 departure.</i>

478
00:40:06.219 --> 00:40:09.173
National Weather Service
is tracking a tropical storm...

479
00:40:09.264 --> 00:40:11.552
...about 75 miles west of us.

480
00:40:12.350 --> 00:40:14.141
Why didn't I build in Orlando?

481
00:40:14.227 --> 00:40:17.975
I'll keep an eye on it.
Maybe it'll swing south like the last one.

482
00:40:22.360 --> 00:40:24.269
Start the tour program.

483
00:40:33.830 --> 00:40:35.703
Hold onto your butts.

484
00:40:45.383 --> 00:40:47.956
<i>And why did they put the fibreglass thing?</i>

485
00:40:58.854 --> 00:41:01.013
<i>You want tojoin the future. right?</i>

486
00:41:01.273 --> 00:41:03.562
<i>God help us when the hands of engineers...</i>

487
00:41:03.651 --> 00:41:06.521
<i>During your tour.
the appropriate information will be...</i>

488
00:41:06.612 --> 00:41:09.281
<i>...automatically selected
and displayed for you.</i>

489
00:41:09.365 --> 00:41:13.030
<i>Simply touch the area of the screen
displaying the appropriate icon.</i>

490
00:41:13.119 --> 00:41:14.399
Are we gonna hit that?

491
00:41:14.495 --> 00:41:16.571
<i>Welcome to Jurassic Park.</i>

492
00:41:20.709 --> 00:41:23.117
What have they got in there. King Kong?

493
00:41:36.684 --> 00:41:39.353
The voice you're now hearing
is Richard Kiley.

494
00:41:39.770 --> 00:41:41.015
We spared no expense.

495
00:41:41.105 --> 00:41:42.563
<i>If you look to the right...</i>

496
00:41:42.648 --> 00:41:47.986
<i>...you'll see a herd of the first dinosaurs
on our tour. called Dilophosaurus.</i>

497
00:41:48.404 --> 00:41:50.526
- Dilophosaurus!
- Shit!

498
00:41:50.823 --> 00:41:52.614
<i>One of the earliest carnivores...</i>

499
00:41:52.699 --> 00:41:55.784
<i>...we now know Dilophosaurus
is actually poisonous...</i>

500
00:41:55.869 --> 00:42:01.077
<i>...spitting its venom at its prey.
causing blindness and paralysis...</i>

501
00:42:01.208 --> 00:42:04.328
<i>...allowing the carnivore
to eat at its leisure.</i>

502
00:42:04.962 --> 00:42:08.662
<i>This makes Dilophosaurus a beautiful
but deadly addition...</i>

503
00:42:08.840 --> 00:42:10.667
<i>...to Jurassic Park.</i>

504
00:42:17.808 --> 00:42:19.302
Alan?

505
00:42:25.440 --> 00:42:26.354
Damn.

506
00:42:31.363 --> 00:42:33.605
Vehicle headlights are on
and not responding.

507
00:42:33.698 --> 00:42:36.189
Those shouldn't be running off
of car batteries.

508
00:42:36.284 --> 00:42:38.858
Item 151 on today's glitch list.

509
00:42:39.162 --> 00:42:42.080
We have all the problems
of a major theme park and a zoo...

510
00:42:42.165 --> 00:42:45.166
...and the computers
aren't even on theirfeet yet.

511
00:42:47.087 --> 00:42:50.871
Our lives are in your hands
and you have butterfingers?

512
00:42:52.550 --> 00:42:54.923
I am totally unappreciated in my time.

513
00:42:55.136 --> 00:42:58.968
You can run this park from this room
with minimal staff for up to three days.

514
00:42:59.057 --> 00:43:01.630
You think that kind of automation is easy?

515
00:43:02.143 --> 00:43:02.973
Or cheap?

516
00:43:03.061 --> 00:43:05.730
You know anyone
who can network eight machines...

517
00:43:05.814 --> 00:43:09.811
...and de-bug two million lines of code
on my salary? If so. I want to see them.

518
00:43:09.901 --> 00:43:14.314
Sorry about yourfinancial problems.
I really am. But they are your problems.

519
00:43:14.405 --> 00:43:16.861
You're absolutely right.
Everything's my problem.

520
00:43:16.950 --> 00:43:22.454
I will not be drawn into another
financial debate with you. I really will not.

521
00:43:22.664 --> 00:43:24.740
There's been hardly any debate at all.

522
00:43:24.832 --> 00:43:27.917
I don't blame people for their mistakes.

523
00:43:28.503 --> 00:43:30.745
But I do ask that they pay for them.

524
00:43:30.963 --> 00:43:32.162
Thanks. Dad.

525
00:43:33.424 --> 00:43:34.420
The headlights.

526
00:43:34.509 --> 00:43:37.178
I'll de-bug the tour program
when they get back. okay?

527
00:43:37.261 --> 00:43:40.512
It'll eat a lot of compute cycles.
We'll lose part of the system.

528
00:43:40.598 --> 00:43:43.848
There's a small amount of memory.
you can't use it for everything.

529
00:43:43.935 --> 00:43:47.054
- Are you gonna compile for a half an hour...
- Quiet. all of you!

530
00:43:48.689 --> 00:43:50.896
They're approaching
the Tyrannosaur paddock.

531
00:44:41.909 --> 00:44:45.492
God creates dinosaurs.
God destroys dinosaurs.

532
00:44:45.913 --> 00:44:50.705
God creates man. Man destroys God.
Man creates dinosaurs.

533
00:44:51.835 --> 00:44:55.833
Dinosaurs eat man.

534
00:44:56.924 --> 00:44:59.000
Woman inherits the earth.

535
00:45:06.600 --> 00:45:09.803
<i>We'll try to tempt the Rex now.
Keep watching the fence.</i>

536
00:45:19.946 --> 00:45:21.820
What's going to happen to the goat?

537
00:45:26.161 --> 00:45:27.869
He's going to eat the goat?

538
00:45:28.205 --> 00:45:29.580
Excellent.

539
00:45:30.665 --> 00:45:33.916
What's the matter. kid?
You never had lamb chops?

540
00:45:34.544 --> 00:45:36.786
I happen to be a vegetarian.

541
00:45:45.138 --> 00:45:48.009
T. Rex doesn't want to be fed.
He wants to hunt.

542
00:45:49.267 --> 00:45:54.059
Can't just suppress 65 million years
of gut instinct.

543
00:46:16.211 --> 00:46:21.169
<i>Eventually you do plan to have dinosaurs
on your dinosaur tour. right?</i>

544
00:46:24.552 --> 00:46:26.877
<i>Hello. Yes?</i>

545
00:46:27.472 --> 00:46:29.464
I really hate that man.

546
00:46:34.687 --> 00:46:39.479
The Tyrannosaur doesn't obey
any set patterns or park schedules.

547
00:46:39.609 --> 00:46:41.482
The essence of chaos.

548
00:46:42.945 --> 00:46:44.903
I'm still not clear on chaos.

549
00:46:46.574 --> 00:46:50.488
It simply deals with unpredictability
in complex systems.

550
00:46:52.038 --> 00:46:54.030
The shorthand is the Butterfly Effect.

551
00:46:54.123 --> 00:46:56.329
A butterfly can flap its wings in Peking...

552
00:46:56.417 --> 00:46:59.252
...and in Central Park
you get rain instead of sunshine.

553
00:47:01.714 --> 00:47:03.707
- Was I going too fast?
- I missed it.

554
00:47:03.799 --> 00:47:04.795
I did a fly-by.

555
00:47:04.884 --> 00:47:07.635
Give me that glass of water.
We'll conduct an experiment.

556
00:47:07.720 --> 00:47:10.840
The car should be still. But that's okay.
It's just an example.

557
00:47:11.390 --> 00:47:13.798
Put your hand flat like a hieroglyphic.

558
00:47:14.643 --> 00:47:16.435
A drop of waterfalls on your hand.

559
00:47:16.520 --> 00:47:19.142
Which way will the drop roll off?
Which finger?

560
00:47:19.565 --> 00:47:21.024
Thumb. I'd say.

561
00:47:23.736 --> 00:47:25.444
Freeze your hand. Don't move.

562
00:47:25.738 --> 00:47:28.774
I'll do the same thing.
start with the same place again.

563
00:47:28.866 --> 00:47:30.325
Which way. now?

564
00:47:30.409 --> 00:47:33.363
Let's say back the same way.

565
00:47:35.748 --> 00:47:38.120
It changed. Why?

566
00:47:38.292 --> 00:47:40.581
Because tiny variations...

567
00:47:41.128 --> 00:47:43.536
...the orientation of the hairs
on your hands...

568
00:47:43.631 --> 00:47:44.959
Alan. look at this.

569
00:47:45.049 --> 00:47:48.916
...the amount of blood distending
your vessels. imperfections in the skin...

570
00:47:49.011 --> 00:47:51.418
- "Imperfections in the skin"?
- Just microscopic.

571
00:47:51.513 --> 00:47:55.096
...never repeat and vastly effect
the outcome. That's...

572
00:47:55.184 --> 00:47:57.223
...what?
- Unpredictability.

573
00:47:59.980 --> 00:48:03.100
There. Look at this. See? I'm right again.

574
00:48:03.233 --> 00:48:07.646
Nobody could predict that Dr. Grant
would jump out of a moving vehicle.

575
00:48:09.865 --> 00:48:12.237
And there's another example.

576
00:48:13.744 --> 00:48:18.204
See. here I am now by myself.
talking to myself. That's Chaos Theory.

577
00:48:19.583 --> 00:48:21.207
Stop the program.

578
00:48:24.504 --> 00:48:28.372
I told you how many times we needed
locking mechanisms on the vehicle doors.

579
00:48:28.467 --> 00:48:31.218
<i>Stopping park vehicles
and rebooting program.</i>

580
00:48:31.678 --> 00:48:33.967
<i>We're on. Will notify for resume.</i>

581
00:48:36.391 --> 00:48:38.467
I'll switch it over to TelePrompTer.

582
00:48:38.560 --> 00:48:41.644
- What about the circuit integrities?
- Screen says faulty sensor.

583
00:48:44.524 --> 00:48:48.059
- I'll call security.
- We're at full go on that and it looks good.

584
00:48:48.320 --> 00:48:51.439
Like I said. there's this other book
by a guy named Bakker...

585
00:48:51.531 --> 00:48:53.820
...and he says dinosaurs died
from diseases.

586
00:48:53.909 --> 00:48:57.242
- Where are we going?
- He didn't say they turned into birds.

587
00:48:57.329 --> 00:48:59.452
Anyone else think
we shouldn't be out here?

588
00:48:59.539 --> 00:49:02.326
And his book was a lot fatter than yours.
Like this.

589
00:49:02.417 --> 00:49:05.169
- Really?
- Yours was fully illustrated.

590
00:49:06.671 --> 00:49:08.000
You okay?

591
00:49:08.131 --> 00:49:10.503
Look at this. Wait. Watch.

592
00:49:11.259 --> 00:49:13.086
Come on. Watch this.

593
00:49:18.808 --> 00:49:20.350
Everybody stay here.

594
00:49:38.578 --> 00:49:40.784
- Okay?
- Of course.

595
00:49:43.708 --> 00:49:47.540
Don't be scared. Come on. it's okay.
Muldoon tranquillised herfor me.

596
00:49:47.628 --> 00:49:48.909
She's sick.

597
00:49:57.805 --> 00:49:59.216
Oh. my God.

598
00:50:21.829 --> 00:50:24.285
She was always my favourite
when I was a kid...

599
00:50:24.373 --> 00:50:27.742
...and now I see
she's the most beautiful thing I ever saw.

600
00:50:32.089 --> 00:50:33.464
It's okay.

601
00:50:36.594 --> 00:50:39.167
Microvesicles. That's interesting.

602
00:50:41.181 --> 00:50:43.470
Thanks. What are her symptoms?

603
00:50:44.059 --> 00:50:46.811
Imbalance. disorientation.
laboured breathing.

604
00:50:46.979 --> 00:50:49.137
It seems to happen every six weeks or so.

605
00:50:49.231 --> 00:50:50.606
Six weeks.

606
00:51:04.246 --> 00:51:05.871
- These are dilated.
- They are?

607
00:51:05.956 --> 00:51:08.625
- Take a look.
- I'll be damned.

608
00:51:09.459 --> 00:51:13.208
That's pharmacological.
From local plant life.

609
00:51:20.637 --> 00:51:22.760
Is this West Indian lilac?

610
00:51:23.223 --> 00:51:26.758
Yes. We know they're toxic.
but the animals don't eat them.

611
00:51:31.189 --> 00:51:34.024
- Are you sure?
- Pretty sure.

612
00:51:35.527 --> 00:51:37.769
There's only one way to be positive.

613
00:51:38.447 --> 00:51:40.984
I'd have to see the dinosaur's droppings.

614
00:51:42.159 --> 00:51:45.278
Dino droppings? Droppings?

615
00:51:51.084 --> 00:51:52.875
Yeah. I got that.

616
00:51:54.379 --> 00:51:57.499
That storm centre hasn't dissipated
or changed course.

617
00:51:57.799 --> 00:52:00.041
We're gonna have to cut the tour short.

618
00:52:00.343 --> 00:52:02.135
We'll pick it up again tomorrow.

619
00:52:02.220 --> 00:52:05.470
- Are you sure we have to?
- It's not worth taking the chance.

620
00:52:05.557 --> 00:52:09.175
- Sustained winds at 45 knots.
- Tell them when they get back in the cars.

621
00:52:09.269 --> 00:52:13.931
Ladies and gentlemen last shuttle leaving
for the dock leaves in five minutes.

622
00:52:14.023 --> 00:52:16.349
Drop what you're doing and leave now.

623
00:52:18.862 --> 00:52:20.024
Damn.

624
00:52:27.453 --> 00:52:29.363
That is one big pile of shit.

625
00:52:36.713 --> 00:52:39.334
You're right.
There's no trace of lilac berries.

626
00:52:39.424 --> 00:52:41.463
That's so odd. though.

627
00:52:41.926 --> 00:52:45.212
All right.
she's suffering from Melia toxicity...

628
00:52:47.265 --> 00:52:49.553
...every six weeks.

629
00:52:51.185 --> 00:52:54.720
Let's see. rats.

630
00:52:55.690 --> 00:52:58.477
She's tenacious.

631
00:52:59.777 --> 00:53:01.485
You have no idea.

632
00:53:03.573 --> 00:53:07.487
You will remember to wash your hands
before you eat anything?

633
00:53:19.714 --> 00:53:23.628
Doctors. if you please.
I have to insist that we get moving.

634
00:53:26.053 --> 00:53:29.636
I'd like to stay with Dr. Harding
and finish up with the Trike.

635
00:53:30.391 --> 00:53:32.182
Sure. I'm in a gas-powered jeep.

636
00:53:32.268 --> 00:53:35.019
I'll drop her off at the centre
before I make the boat.

637
00:53:35.104 --> 00:53:37.939
Great. Then I'll catch up with you later.

638
00:53:38.023 --> 00:53:38.972
You sure?

639
00:53:39.066 --> 00:53:41.853
Yeah. I want to stay
with her a little longer.

640
00:53:41.944 --> 00:53:43.355
Okay. then.

641
00:53:58.168 --> 00:54:02.166
<i>There's nothing I can do.
The captain says we have to go. we go.</i>

642
00:54:02.548 --> 00:54:04.256
You've got to give me time.

643
00:54:04.341 --> 00:54:08.006
I did a test run. it took me 20 minutes.
I think I can push it to 18 but...

644
00:54:08.095 --> 00:54:10.218
...you've got to give me
at least 15 minutes.

645
00:54:10.305 --> 00:54:11.634
<i>No promises.</i>

646
00:54:19.398 --> 00:54:21.971
Visitor vehicles are returning
to the garage.

647
00:54:24.319 --> 00:54:29.527
So much for ourfirst tour.
Two no-shows and one sick Triceratops.

648
00:54:30.742 --> 00:54:32.201
It could've been worse.

649
00:54:33.662 --> 00:54:34.942
A lot worse.

650
00:54:35.080 --> 00:54:39.160
Anybody want a soda or something?
I'm going up to the machine.

651
00:54:39.251 --> 00:54:41.409
I thought maybe
I'd get somebody something.

652
00:54:41.503 --> 00:54:45.251
I've had only sweets
and I'm gonna get something salty.

653
00:54:46.091 --> 00:54:48.333
I finished de-bugging the phones.

654
00:54:49.636 --> 00:54:51.676
I was going to. so I did.

655
00:54:51.930 --> 00:54:54.551
So I de-bugged the phones.
And I thought maybe...

656
00:54:55.058 --> 00:54:57.810
...I should tell you the system
will be compiling...

657
00:54:57.894 --> 00:55:00.765
...for 18 to 20 minutes.
so some of the minor systems...

658
00:55:00.855 --> 00:55:04.474
...they might go on and off for a while.
but it's nothing to worry about.

659
00:55:26.798 --> 00:55:31.045
- Do you have any kids?
- Me? Hell. yeah. Three. I love kids.

660
00:55:33.012 --> 00:55:35.384
Anything at all can and does happen.

661
00:55:35.890 --> 00:55:38.381
Same with wives. for that matter.

662
00:55:38.810 --> 00:55:41.265
- You're married?
- Occasionally.

663
00:55:43.314 --> 00:55:47.691
I'm always on the lookout
for a future ex-Mrs. Malcolm.

664
00:56:01.249 --> 00:56:03.656
Five. four...

665
00:56:15.846 --> 00:56:18.135
- That's odd.
- What?

666
00:56:18.391 --> 00:56:20.549
Door security systems are shutting down.

667
00:56:20.893 --> 00:56:24.096
Nedry said a few systems
would go off-line. didn't he?

668
00:57:20.244 --> 00:57:22.070
By the way. Dr. Sattler...

669
00:57:23.247 --> 00:57:26.662
...she's not. like. available. is she?
- Why?

670
00:57:29.586 --> 00:57:32.373
- I'm sorry. You two are...
- Yeah.

671
00:57:35.759 --> 00:57:39.507
- What'd I touch?
- You didn't touch anything. We stopped.

672
00:57:48.396 --> 00:57:50.104
What the hell?

673
00:57:50.190 --> 00:57:53.191
- What now?
- Fences are failing all over the park.

674
00:57:53.610 --> 00:57:55.768
Find Nedry. Check the vending machines.

675
00:58:27.685 --> 00:58:29.761
Just look at this work station.

676
00:58:29.854 --> 00:58:33.354
- What a complete slob.
- The Raptorfences aren't out. are they?

677
00:58:40.365 --> 00:58:42.108
No. no. They're still on.

678
00:58:44.744 --> 00:58:47.282
Why the hell would he turn
the other ones off?

679
00:59:27.370 --> 00:59:29.030
Access main program.

680
00:59:29.872 --> 00:59:31.532
Access main security.

681
00:59:32.291 --> 00:59:33.999
Access main program grid.

682
00:59:43.135 --> 00:59:45.211
<i>You didn't say the magic word.</i>

683
00:59:45.638 --> 00:59:49.172
Please! Goddamn it.
I hate this hacker crap.

684
00:59:49.308 --> 00:59:52.558
Phone Nedry's people in Cambridge.

685
00:59:54.980 --> 00:59:56.522
Phones are out. too.

686
01:00:00.069 --> 01:00:01.729
Where did the vehicles stop?

687
01:00:22.883 --> 01:00:24.294
Their radio's out. too.

688
01:00:24.927 --> 01:00:27.168
- Gennaro said to stay put.
- Kids okay?

689
01:00:27.346 --> 01:00:29.504
I didn't ask. Why wouldn't they be?

690
01:00:29.598 --> 01:00:31.306
- Kids get scared.
- What's scary?

691
01:00:31.391 --> 01:00:34.476
- It's just a little hiccup in the power.
- I'm not scared.

692
01:00:34.603 --> 01:00:36.642
- I didn't say you were scared.
- I know.

693
01:00:40.275 --> 01:00:42.600
Hey. where did you find those?

694
01:00:42.819 --> 01:00:45.441
- In the box. under my seat.
- Are they heavy?

695
01:00:45.906 --> 01:00:48.575
- Yeah.
- Then they're expensive. Put them back.

696
01:00:55.749 --> 01:00:57.326
Don't scare me.

697
01:01:08.887 --> 01:01:10.678
Cool. Night vision.

698
01:01:35.955 --> 01:01:37.414
Did you feel that?

699
01:02:11.365 --> 01:02:13.987
Maybe it's the power
trying to come back on.

700
01:02:16.621 --> 01:02:17.901
What is that?

701
01:02:35.056 --> 01:02:36.431
Where's the goat?

702
01:02:59.496 --> 01:03:00.694
Jesus!

703
01:03:05.586 --> 01:03:07.377
He left us.

704
01:03:18.682 --> 01:03:23.011
- Where does he think he's going?
- When you gotta go. you gotta go.

705
01:03:41.121 --> 01:03:42.401
Dr. Grant.

706
01:03:55.302 --> 01:03:57.425
I hate being right all the time.

707
01:04:06.897 --> 01:04:11.060
Keep absolutely still.
Its vision is based on movement.

708
01:04:25.081 --> 01:04:26.623
Turn the light off.

709
01:04:31.546 --> 01:04:33.005
Turn the light off!

710
01:05:28.853 --> 01:05:31.723
- Hurry! Turn it off!
- I'm sorry!

711
01:05:35.901 --> 01:05:37.894
You're the one who turned it...

712
01:06:56.898 --> 01:06:58.227
Ian. freeze!

713
01:06:58.733 --> 01:07:00.144
Get the kids!

714
01:07:01.111 --> 01:07:03.436
- Get rid of the flare!
- Get the kids!

715
01:07:04.447 --> 01:07:06.025
Get rid of the flare!

716
01:07:08.994 --> 01:07:10.820
Hail Mary. full of grace. the Lord be...

717
01:07:33.268 --> 01:07:34.513
Dr. Grant!

718
01:07:39.149 --> 01:07:41.722
I'm stuck. The seat's got my feet.

719
01:07:41.818 --> 01:07:44.107
I'll get you next. You're okay.

720
01:07:45.488 --> 01:07:46.863
You're all right.

721
01:07:47.615 --> 01:07:49.193
Tim. Tim!

722
01:07:52.912 --> 01:07:55.830
Don't move.
He can't see us if we don't move.

723
01:09:01.230 --> 01:09:03.306
Lex! Lex. you're choking me.

724
01:09:06.151 --> 01:09:07.396
Grab the wire.

725
01:09:27.131 --> 01:09:30.998
"Keycheck space minus 0.
Keychecks off. safety space minus 0."

726
01:09:31.135 --> 01:09:34.338
He's turning the safety systems off.
Doesn't want anybody to see.

727
01:09:34.429 --> 01:09:37.633
Look at this next entry.
It's the kicker. "White rabbit object. "

728
01:09:37.808 --> 01:09:41.758
It did it all. With the keychecks off.
the computer didn't file the keystrokes.

729
01:09:41.853 --> 01:09:45.554
The way to find them is to check
the computer's lines of code one by one.

730
01:09:45.691 --> 01:09:48.857
- How many lines of code are there?
- About two million.

731
01:09:49.111 --> 01:09:50.521
- Two million?
- Yeah.

732
01:09:53.490 --> 01:09:58.199
Robert. I wonder if perhaps you would
be good enough to take a gas jeep...

733
01:09:59.788 --> 01:10:02.030
...and bring back my grandchildren.

734
01:10:02.916 --> 01:10:03.947
Sure.

735
01:10:06.878 --> 01:10:08.372
I'm going with him.

736
01:10:11.716 --> 01:10:12.748
John.

737
01:10:18.723 --> 01:10:22.223
I can't get Jurassic Park back on-line
without Dennis Nedry.

738
01:10:42.372 --> 01:10:43.534
Damn it!

739
01:10:50.255 --> 01:10:51.665
There's the road!

740
01:10:58.221 --> 01:11:02.265
Winch this sucker off the thing
and then I tie it to the that thing there.

741
01:11:02.350 --> 01:11:05.766
I'll pull down this thing here.
and pull it back up again.

742
01:11:14.070 --> 01:11:17.521
My glasses. I can afford more glasses!

743
01:11:46.727 --> 01:11:50.061
You've got time. You can do it.
Do it. Come on. Dennis.

744
01:11:57.488 --> 01:11:58.519
Hello.

745
01:12:03.661 --> 01:12:06.448
Yeah. that's nice. I've got to go.

746
01:12:17.675 --> 01:12:19.003
Nice boy.

747
01:12:19.426 --> 01:12:20.505
Nice boy.

748
01:12:21.095 --> 01:12:22.719
Nice dinosaur.

749
01:12:23.555 --> 01:12:26.971
Thought you were one of your big brothers.
You're not so bad.

750
01:12:27.059 --> 01:12:30.973
What do you want? A little food?
Look at me. I just fell down a hill.

751
01:12:31.063 --> 01:12:34.562
I'm soaking wet. I don't have any food.
I have nothing on me.

752
01:12:35.943 --> 01:12:38.149
Go on. Play fetch?

753
01:12:40.322 --> 01:12:41.520
Look. stick.

754
01:12:43.200 --> 01:12:45.358
Look at stick.

755
01:12:46.036 --> 01:12:48.953
Stick. stupid.
Fetch the stick. boy. Look at the stick.

756
01:12:49.706 --> 01:12:52.032
You like the stick? Go on and get it.

757
01:12:52.209 --> 01:12:54.036
No wonder you're extinct.

758
01:12:55.295 --> 01:12:57.537
I'm gonna run you over
when I come back down.

759
01:14:13.998 --> 01:14:15.576
Timmy!

760
01:14:19.670 --> 01:14:21.710
Now. Lex. Listen.

761
01:14:22.423 --> 01:14:24.083
Lex. I'm right here.

762
01:14:24.759 --> 01:14:27.214
I'll look after you.
I have to help your brother.

763
01:14:27.345 --> 01:14:29.551
Stay right here and wait for me.

764
01:14:29.931 --> 01:14:32.256
He left us.

765
01:14:32.767 --> 01:14:35.258
But that's not what I'm going to do.

766
01:14:37.313 --> 01:14:38.344
Okay?

767
01:14:40.942 --> 01:14:42.056
Stay here.

768
01:15:09.303 --> 01:15:11.212
You hear me? I'm coming up.

769
01:15:11.931 --> 01:15:15.880
I hate climbing. I hate trees. way too high.

770
01:15:44.171 --> 01:15:45.250
You okay?

771
01:15:48.258 --> 01:15:49.503
I threw up.

772
01:15:52.638 --> 01:15:53.836
That's okay.

773
01:15:54.806 --> 01:15:56.514
Just give me your hand.

774
01:16:00.687 --> 01:16:04.732
Tim. I won't tell anyone you threw up.
Just give me your hand.

775
01:16:13.784 --> 01:16:15.112
Here. I've got you.

776
01:16:16.912 --> 01:16:17.943
Okay.

777
01:16:18.497 --> 01:16:22.328
- That's good. Over the rail.
- Don't pull me too hard.

778
01:16:26.880 --> 01:16:29.122
Stand on the door. Hang on to me.

779
01:16:32.761 --> 01:16:35.465
- That's not too bad. right. Timmy?
- Yes. it is.

780
01:16:35.555 --> 01:16:38.260
It's like a tree house.
Your dad ever build you one?

781
01:16:38.350 --> 01:16:39.892
- No.
- Yeah. me. too.

782
01:16:41.561 --> 01:16:44.348
The thing about climbing is.
you never look down.

783
01:16:44.439 --> 01:16:46.016
This is impossible.

784
01:16:46.316 --> 01:16:50.563
- How am I going to do this? It's about...
- I'm going to help you with yourfooting.

785
01:16:56.326 --> 01:16:57.357
Tim. go.

786
01:17:19.974 --> 01:17:21.433
Go. Tim. go!

787
01:17:29.734 --> 01:17:30.932
Faster. Tim!

788
01:17:37.658 --> 01:17:38.773
Tim. jump!

789
01:17:42.788 --> 01:17:43.868
Go. Tim.

790
01:17:52.340 --> 01:17:54.747
We're back in the car again.

791
01:17:56.969 --> 01:17:59.045
At least you're out of the tree.

792
01:18:04.435 --> 01:18:06.059
Where's the other car?

793
01:18:09.315 --> 01:18:10.477
Alan!

794
01:18:11.609 --> 01:18:12.854
Dr. Grant!

795
01:18:29.001 --> 01:18:32.417
- I think this was Gennaro.
- I think this was. too.

796
01:18:36.008 --> 01:18:38.546
- I think it's ahead of us.
- It could be anywhere.

797
01:18:38.635 --> 01:18:42.004
With fences down.
it can wander in and out of any paddock.

798
01:18:49.021 --> 01:18:51.013
He's put a tourniquet on. Lan.

799
01:18:52.733 --> 01:18:55.437
Remind me to thank John
for a lovely weekend.

800
01:19:00.449 --> 01:19:02.192
Can we chance moving him?

801
01:19:03.535 --> 01:19:04.994
Please chance it.

802
01:19:13.545 --> 01:19:15.123
Ellie. come on!

803
01:19:22.679 --> 01:19:23.758
The other car!

804
01:19:24.514 --> 01:19:25.759
Dr. Grant?

805
01:19:30.270 --> 01:19:31.764
They're not here.

806
01:20:01.134 --> 01:20:02.628
Anybody hear that?

807
01:20:06.222 --> 01:20:08.630
It's an impact tremor. is what it is.

808
01:20:09.517 --> 01:20:11.308
I'm fairly alarmed here.

809
01:20:12.770 --> 01:20:15.440
Come on. We've got to get out of here.
Now!

810
01:20:17.275 --> 01:20:18.354
Let's go.

811
01:20:29.829 --> 01:20:31.109
Must go faster.

812
01:20:33.791 --> 01:20:36.626
Here it comes! Stand on it! Fifth gear!

813
01:20:42.967 --> 01:20:46.087
- Get off the stick! Bloody move!
- Look out!

814
01:21:13.205 --> 01:21:15.530
Think they'll have that on the tour?

815
01:21:23.716 --> 01:21:25.293
Are you hearing this?

816
01:21:31.890 --> 01:21:34.049
Come on. Tim. Hurry up.

817
01:21:35.018 --> 01:21:36.726
Let's get up this tree.

818
01:21:39.690 --> 01:21:42.441
Come on. Tim. it's okay.
Listen. Try up here.

819
01:21:46.780 --> 01:21:48.109
I hate trees.

820
01:21:48.782 --> 01:21:52.400
- They don't bother me.
- Yeah? Well. you weren't in the last one.

821
01:22:06.925 --> 01:22:10.460
Look at the Brontosauruses.
I mean. Brachiosaurus.

822
01:22:12.013 --> 01:22:13.424
They're singing.

823
01:22:42.669 --> 01:22:44.496
Don't let the monsters come here.

824
01:22:44.587 --> 01:22:48.003
They're not monsters. they're animals.
These are herbivores.

825
01:22:48.258 --> 01:22:51.627
They only eat vegetables.
For you. I think they'd make an exception.

826
01:22:51.719 --> 01:22:53.379
I hate the other kind.

827
01:22:55.473 --> 01:22:58.260
The other kind just do what they do.

828
01:23:18.371 --> 01:23:19.569
What's that?

829
01:23:24.794 --> 01:23:28.578
What are you and Ellie going to do.
if you don't dig up bones anymore?

830
01:23:30.174 --> 01:23:31.419
I don't know.

831
01:23:32.677 --> 01:23:35.084
I guess we'll just have to evolve. too.

832
01:23:38.766 --> 01:23:40.972
What do you call a blind dinosaur?

833
01:23:42.979 --> 01:23:46.395
- What do you call a blind dinosaur?
- "Do-you-think-he-saurus. "

834
01:23:50.695 --> 01:23:53.186
What do you call a blind dinosaur's dog?

835
01:23:54.031 --> 01:23:55.194
You got me.

836
01:23:55.533 --> 01:23:57.525
A "Do-you-think-he-saurus' Rex. "

837
01:24:00.246 --> 01:24:02.238
- Alan?
- Yeah?

838
01:24:03.082 --> 01:24:06.249
What if the dinosaurs come back
while we're all asleep?

839
01:24:08.546 --> 01:24:10.752
- I'll stay awake.
- All night?

840
01:24:13.342 --> 01:24:14.457
All night.

841
01:25:04.726 --> 01:25:06.351
They were all melting.

842
01:25:10.065 --> 01:25:13.185
Malcolm's okay for now.
I gave him a shot of morphine.

843
01:25:17.072 --> 01:25:18.614
They'll all be fine.

844
01:25:19.616 --> 01:25:23.910
Who better to get the children through
Jurassic Park than a dinosaur expert?

845
01:25:28.375 --> 01:25:30.166
You know. the first...

846
01:25:31.419 --> 01:25:34.871
...attraction I ever built
when I came down from Scotland...

847
01:25:36.550 --> 01:25:39.041
...was a flea circus. Petticoat Lane.

848
01:25:40.428 --> 01:25:42.220
Really quite wonderful.

849
01:25:42.806 --> 01:25:46.056
I had a wee trapeze and a...

850
01:25:49.270 --> 01:25:50.469
...carousel...

851
01:25:54.401 --> 01:25:55.811
...and a seesaw.

852
01:25:56.945 --> 01:25:59.151
They all move motorised. of course.

853
01:25:59.489 --> 01:26:02.194
People said they saw the fleas.
"I can see the fleas.

854
01:26:02.283 --> 01:26:04.027
"Can't you see the fleas?"

855
01:26:04.786 --> 01:26:09.080
Clown fleas. high-wire fleas.
and fleas on parade.

856
01:26:15.296 --> 01:26:16.672
With this place...

857
01:26:18.883 --> 01:26:22.252
...I wanted to show them something
that wasn't an illusion.

858
01:26:23.262 --> 01:26:26.382
Something that was real.
Something that they could...

859
01:26:29.519 --> 01:26:30.977
...see and touch.

860
01:26:35.733 --> 01:26:38.141
An aim not devoid of merit.

861
01:26:42.657 --> 01:26:46.275
But you can't think through this one. John.
You have to feel it.

862
01:26:48.496 --> 01:26:50.239
You're absolutely right.

863
01:26:52.041 --> 01:26:54.330
Hiring Nedry was a mistake.
that's obvious.

864
01:26:54.460 --> 01:26:57.165
We're overdependent on automation.
I can see that now.

865
01:26:57.254 --> 01:26:59.876
Next time. everything's correctable.

866
01:27:00.675 --> 01:27:03.878
Creation is an act of sheer will.

867
01:27:06.222 --> 01:27:08.179
Next time. it'll be flawless.

868
01:27:08.766 --> 01:27:12.099
It's still the flea circus. It's all an illusion.

869
01:27:12.228 --> 01:27:13.722
When we have control...

870
01:27:13.813 --> 01:27:16.482
You've never had control!
That's the illusion.

871
01:27:16.649 --> 01:27:19.318
I was overwhelmed
by the power of this place.

872
01:27:20.736 --> 01:27:22.147
I made a mistake. too.

873
01:27:22.279 --> 01:27:26.063
I didn't have enough respect
for that power. and it's out now.

874
01:27:28.702 --> 01:27:31.869
The only thing that matters now
are the people we love.

875
01:27:34.041 --> 01:27:36.164
Alan. Lex. and Tim.

876
01:27:37.795 --> 01:27:40.914
John. they're out there.
where people are dying.

877
01:27:57.981 --> 01:27:59.096
It's good.

878
01:28:03.070 --> 01:28:04.528
Spared no expense.

879
01:28:31.890 --> 01:28:35.057
- Go away!
- It's okay. It's a Brachiosaurus.

880
01:28:35.727 --> 01:28:38.396
It's a "Veggie-saurus". Lex.
"Veggie-saurus. "

881
01:28:38.939 --> 01:28:39.970
Veggie.

882
01:28:41.066 --> 01:28:42.857
Come on. Come on. girl.

883
01:28:47.072 --> 01:28:48.447
Come on. baby.

884
01:28:54.871 --> 01:28:56.365
I'm not letting go.

885
01:29:08.301 --> 01:29:11.136
- It looks like it has a cold.
- Yeah. Maybe.

886
01:29:11.513 --> 01:29:13.137
- Can I touch it?
- Sure.

887
01:29:13.473 --> 01:29:16.509
Just think of it as kind of a big cow.

888
01:29:19.896 --> 01:29:21.094
I like cows.

889
01:29:31.157 --> 01:29:33.482
Come on. girl. Come on up here. girl.

890
01:29:40.958 --> 01:29:42.203
God bless you.

891
01:29:48.591 --> 01:29:51.508
Great. Now she'll never try anything new.

892
01:29:52.053 --> 01:29:55.089
She'll sit in her room. never come out.
play on her computer.

893
01:29:55.181 --> 01:29:57.968
- I'm a hacker.
- That's what I said. You're a nerd.

894
01:29:58.059 --> 01:30:01.309
I am not a computer nerd.
I prefer to be called a hacker.

895
01:30:01.520 --> 01:30:02.635
God.

896
01:30:07.610 --> 01:30:09.234
You know what this is?

897
01:30:11.155 --> 01:30:13.148
It's a dinosaur egg.

898
01:30:13.866 --> 01:30:17.069
The dinosaurs are breeding.

899
01:30:20.247 --> 01:30:24.327
But my grandpa said
all the dinosaurs were girls.

900
01:30:25.711 --> 01:30:27.953
- Amphibian DNA.
- What's that?

901
01:30:31.842 --> 01:30:36.884
The film said they used frog DNA
to fill in the gene-sequence gaps.

902
01:30:36.972 --> 01:30:40.258
They mutated the dinosaur genetic code.

903
01:30:41.310 --> 01:30:43.552
And blended it with that of frogs.

904
01:30:46.482 --> 01:30:50.942
Some West African frogs have been known
to change sex from male to female...

905
01:30:51.028 --> 01:30:53.067
...in a single sex environment.

906
01:30:55.073 --> 01:30:56.616
Malcolm was right.

907
01:30:58.035 --> 01:30:59.066
Look.

908
01:31:07.836 --> 01:31:09.544
Life found a way.

909
01:31:12.883 --> 01:31:16.880
That's crazy. You're out of your mind.
He's absolutely out of his mind.

910
01:31:17.137 --> 01:31:19.343
Wait. What exactly would this mean?

911
01:31:19.431 --> 01:31:23.298
We're talking about a calculated risk.
which is the only option left to us.

912
01:31:23.393 --> 01:31:27.806
We'll neverfind the command Nedry used.
He's covered his tracks far too well.

913
01:31:28.356 --> 01:31:31.192
I think it's obvious now
that he's not coming back.

914
01:31:31.276 --> 01:31:35.819
- So. shutting down the entire system...
- Get somebody else. I won't do it.

915
01:31:35.906 --> 01:31:41.113
Shutting down the system is the only way
to wipe out everything he did.

916
01:31:42.204 --> 01:31:45.786
Now. as I understand it.
all the systems will then come back...

917
01:31:45.957 --> 01:31:48.662
...on their original start-up mode. Correct?

918
01:31:49.210 --> 01:31:52.211
Theoretically. yes.
We've never shut down before.

919
01:31:52.297 --> 01:31:55.298
- It may not come back on.
- Would we get the phones back?

920
01:31:55.383 --> 01:31:57.008
Yes. again. in theory.

921
01:31:57.635 --> 01:32:01.051
What about the lysine contingency?
We could put that into effect.

922
01:32:01.139 --> 01:32:03.974
- What's that?
- That's absolutely out of the question.

923
01:32:04.058 --> 01:32:06.894
The lysine contingency
prevents the spread of animals...

924
01:32:06.978 --> 01:32:08.852
...if they ever get off the island.

925
01:32:08.938 --> 01:32:12.603
Wu inserted a gene that creates
a faulty enzyme in protein metabolism.

926
01:32:12.692 --> 01:32:15.610
The animals can't manufacture
the amino acid. lysine.

927
01:32:15.695 --> 01:32:19.444
Unless they're supplied with lysine by us.
they slip into a coma and die.

928
01:32:19.532 --> 01:32:21.988
People are dying.

929
01:32:26.205 --> 01:32:28.578
Will you please shut down the system?

930
01:32:50.605 --> 01:32:52.265
Hold on to your butts.

931
01:33:12.168 --> 01:33:13.282
It's okay.

932
01:33:13.419 --> 01:33:16.088
Look. see that? It's on. It worked.

933
01:33:18.591 --> 01:33:20.963
What do you mean it worked?
Everything's off.

934
01:33:21.051 --> 01:33:25.180
Shutdown tripped the circuit breakers.
Turn them back on. reboot a few systems:

935
01:33:25.264 --> 01:33:28.633
Telephones. security doors.
half dozen others. but it worked.

936
01:33:28.726 --> 01:33:31.133
- System's ready.
- Where are the breakers?

937
01:33:31.228 --> 01:33:32.936
The shed at end of the compound.

938
01:33:33.022 --> 01:33:35.773
Three minutes. I'll have the power back on
in the park.

939
01:33:35.858 --> 01:33:38.942
Just to be safe. I want everybody
in the emergency bunker...

940
01:33:39.028 --> 01:33:42.361
...until Mr. Arnold returns.
and the whole system's running again.

941
01:33:42.656 --> 01:33:44.779
- I'm tired. I'm hot.
- I'm dirty.

942
01:33:45.784 --> 01:33:49.449
Looking at the map.
I'd say the visitor's centre is just a mile...

943
01:33:50.205 --> 01:33:51.913
...over that rise there.

944
01:33:56.378 --> 01:33:57.409
What is that?

945
01:34:00.174 --> 01:34:02.380
Tim. can you tell me what they are?

946
01:34:09.433 --> 01:34:10.678
Gallimimus.

947
01:34:10.767 --> 01:34:13.258
Are those meat-eating?

948
01:34:14.896 --> 01:34:16.177
"Meat-asauruses"?

949
01:34:21.194 --> 01:34:23.650
Look at the wheeling.
Uniform direction changes.

950
01:34:23.739 --> 01:34:26.443
Just like a flock of birds
evading a predator.

951
01:34:27.951 --> 01:34:31.071
They're flocking this way.

952
01:35:14.038 --> 01:35:16.245
- I want to go now.
- Just look how it eats.

953
01:35:16.332 --> 01:35:17.364
Please.

954
01:35:17.709 --> 01:35:20.460
I bet you'll never look at birds
the same way again.

955
01:35:20.545 --> 01:35:22.621
- Yes.
- Go now.

956
01:35:24.465 --> 01:35:27.135
Okay. Keep low and follow me.

957
01:35:29.554 --> 01:35:31.345
Look how much blood.

958
01:35:33.558 --> 01:35:35.681
God. Something went wrong.

959
01:35:36.561 --> 01:35:40.095
Something's happened.
Something's wrong.

960
01:35:42.817 --> 01:35:44.395
This is just a delay.

961
01:35:44.485 --> 01:35:47.570
That's all it is.
All major theme parks have delays.

962
01:35:47.822 --> 01:35:52.151
When they opened Disneyland in 1956.
nothing worked.

963
01:35:52.577 --> 01:35:56.277
If the Pirates of the Caribbean
breaks down. the pirates don't eat tourists.

964
01:35:56.372 --> 01:36:01.248
I can't wait any more. Something's wrong.
I'm gonna go get the power back on.

965
01:36:01.544 --> 01:36:04.628
You can't just stroll down the road.
you know.

966
01:36:04.797 --> 01:36:08.083
Don't let's be too hasty.
I mean. he's only been gone...

967
01:36:10.761 --> 01:36:12.801
- I'm going with you.
- Okay.

968
01:36:28.445 --> 01:36:29.477
Sorry.

969
01:36:33.492 --> 01:36:37.739
Now. this isn't going to be just like
switching on the kitchen light.

970
01:36:37.871 --> 01:36:41.240
But I think I can follow this
and then talk you through it.

971
01:36:45.838 --> 01:36:46.833
Right.

972
01:36:52.886 --> 01:36:54.926
It ought to be me. really. going.

973
01:36:55.013 --> 01:36:57.849
- Why?
- I'm a... And you're a...

974
01:36:59.351 --> 01:37:01.676
- Look.
- Come on. let's go.

975
01:37:01.770 --> 01:37:05.020
We can discuss sexism
in survival situations when I get back.

976
01:37:05.107 --> 01:37:08.725
You just take me through this step by step.
I'm on Channel 2.

977
01:37:45.730 --> 01:37:48.482
The shutdown must've turned off
all the fences.

978
01:37:49.109 --> 01:37:52.774
Damn it. even Nedry knew better
than to mess with the Raptor pen.

979
01:37:58.743 --> 01:37:59.906
Come on. this way.

980
01:38:07.419 --> 01:38:09.376
I can see the shed from here.

981
01:38:09.587 --> 01:38:11.331
We can make it if we run.

982
01:38:11.673 --> 01:38:14.211
No. We can't.

983
01:38:15.135 --> 01:38:16.166
Why not?

984
01:38:16.928 --> 01:38:18.885
Because we're being hunted.

985
01:38:20.223 --> 01:38:22.216
In the bushes. straight ahead.

986
01:38:24.852 --> 01:38:26.133
It's all right.

987
01:38:26.729 --> 01:38:28.105
Like hell it is.

988
01:38:29.440 --> 01:38:32.607
Run. Towards the shed.

989
01:38:34.821 --> 01:38:36.279
I've got her.

990
01:38:37.240 --> 01:38:38.734
Go. Now!

991
01:38:57.927 --> 01:38:59.302
Mr. Arnold?

992
01:39:04.642 --> 01:39:05.887
John. I'm in.

993
01:39:06.477 --> 01:39:07.426
<i>Great.</i>

994
01:39:08.980 --> 01:39:12.479
Ahead of you is a metal staircase.
Go down it.

995
01:39:13.526 --> 01:39:15.814
<i>Okay. Going down.</i>

996
01:39:16.737 --> 01:39:20.652
After 20 or 30 feet
you come to a T-junction. Take a left.

997
01:39:20.741 --> 01:39:23.861
- Have herfollow the main cable.
- I know how to read a schematic.

998
01:39:54.024 --> 01:39:56.231
I guess that means the power's off.

999
01:40:09.498 --> 01:40:12.119
- That's not funny.
- That was great.

1000
01:40:14.628 --> 01:40:16.537
Well. maybe we. we could...

1001
01:40:34.398 --> 01:40:36.889
Damn it. Dead end.

1002
01:40:37.275 --> 01:40:38.520
Wait a minute.

1003
01:40:40.070 --> 01:40:43.355
There should have been a right turn
back there somewhere.

1004
01:40:44.324 --> 01:40:45.273
Look above you.

1005
01:40:46.785 --> 01:40:50.652
<i>There should be a bundle of cable and
pipes all heading in the same direction.</i>

1006
01:40:50.747 --> 01:40:51.910
Follow that.

1007
01:40:52.582 --> 01:40:54.741
Okay. Following the piping.

1008
01:40:57.420 --> 01:41:01.881
I bet I could climb over to the other side
before you could even get to the top.

1009
01:41:01.967 --> 01:41:04.292
- What would you give me?
- Respect.

1010
01:41:05.261 --> 01:41:07.301
Come on. guys. it's not a race.

1011
01:41:08.973 --> 01:41:10.218
I see the box.

1012
01:41:11.976 --> 01:41:13.684
It says. "High Voltage. "

1013
01:41:18.066 --> 01:41:19.062
Okay.

1014
01:41:23.154 --> 01:41:25.823
Good. Here we go.

1015
01:41:26.491 --> 01:41:27.689
Over the top.

1016
01:41:28.326 --> 01:41:29.951
Take your time.

1017
01:41:30.954 --> 01:41:31.949
Good. Come on.

1018
01:41:32.705 --> 01:41:34.614
Find yourfooting.

1019
01:41:36.876 --> 01:41:39.581
You can't throw the main switch by hand.

1020
01:41:39.671 --> 01:41:43.086
You've got to pump up the primer handle
in order to get the charge.

1021
01:41:43.174 --> 01:41:45.499
It's large. flat and grey.

1022
01:41:46.302 --> 01:41:48.211
All right. here I go. Okay?

1023
01:41:49.722 --> 01:41:55.013
One. two. three. four.

1024
01:41:55.311 --> 01:41:56.936
Okay. charged.

1025
01:41:57.647 --> 01:42:01.431
Under the words "Contact Position."
there's a round green button...

1026
01:42:01.734 --> 01:42:04.059
...which says "Push to Close. "

1027
01:42:04.612 --> 01:42:06.439
Push to close.

1028
01:42:09.951 --> 01:42:10.946
Push it.

1029
01:42:26.175 --> 01:42:30.125
The red buttons turn on
the individual park systems.

1030
01:42:31.013 --> 01:42:32.176
Switch them on.

1031
01:42:43.817 --> 01:42:46.024
- Get down now!
- You're gonna have to jump.

1032
01:42:46.111 --> 01:42:47.855
You crazy? I'm not gonna jump.

1033
01:42:48.030 --> 01:42:50.651
- Do what Dr. Grant says!
- Let go. I'll count to three.

1034
01:42:50.741 --> 01:42:53.149
One. two. three!

1035
01:42:57.247 --> 01:42:58.991
I'm coming up to get you.

1036
01:42:59.083 --> 01:43:00.577
I've got to get Tim.

1037
01:43:01.001 --> 01:43:02.745
Okay. I'm gonna count to three.

1038
01:43:05.339 --> 01:43:06.335
One...

1039
01:43:08.300 --> 01:43:09.379
...two...

1040
01:43:20.479 --> 01:43:21.641
He's not breathing.

1041
01:43:26.902 --> 01:43:29.274
I think we're back in business!

1042
01:45:09.086 --> 01:45:10.331
Clever girl.

1043
01:45:34.653 --> 01:45:35.685
No. Tim!

1044
01:45:38.699 --> 01:45:40.573
Good boy.

1045
01:45:45.164 --> 01:45:46.362
Three.

1046
01:45:51.545 --> 01:45:52.624
Hello?

1047
01:46:04.475 --> 01:46:06.633
I'm gonna have to find the others.

1048
01:46:07.311 --> 01:46:10.062
Get you to a doctor.

1049
01:46:12.107 --> 01:46:14.396
- Lex. you look after Tim.
- Yeah.

1050
01:46:15.694 --> 01:46:17.651
Your hair is all sticking up.

1051
01:46:19.656 --> 01:46:21.945
Big Tim. the human piece of toast.

1052
01:46:26.246 --> 01:46:28.405
I'll be back soon. I promise.

1053
01:46:55.734 --> 01:46:56.730
Run.

1054
01:48:13.352 --> 01:48:15.262
Just the two Raptors. right?

1055
01:48:16.772 --> 01:48:18.646
You sure the third one's contained?

1056
01:48:18.733 --> 01:48:22.315
Yes. unless they figure out
how to open doors.

1057
01:48:48.929 --> 01:48:52.096
- What is it?
- It's a Velociraptor.

1058
01:48:54.893 --> 01:48:56.388
It's inside.

1059
01:49:21.962 --> 01:49:23.041
Follow me.

1060
01:51:58.617 --> 01:51:59.862
It's in there.

1061
01:52:00.744 --> 01:52:01.989
Control room.

1062
01:52:08.335 --> 01:52:11.621
- We can call for help?
- We've got to reboot the system first.

1063
01:52:14.466 --> 01:52:15.664
The door locks!

1064
01:52:16.677 --> 01:52:18.716
Ellie. boot up the door locks!

1065
01:52:28.230 --> 01:52:30.057
No. boot up the door locks!

1066
01:52:31.108 --> 01:52:34.940
- Get back! Boot up the door locks.
- You can't hold it by yourself!

1067
01:52:43.370 --> 01:52:46.869
It's a UNIX system. I know this.

1068
01:52:47.624 --> 01:52:49.700
It's all the files of the whole park.

1069
01:52:49.793 --> 01:52:53.043
It tells you everything.
I've got to find the right file.

1070
01:52:53.797 --> 01:52:55.374
Try to reach the gun.

1071
01:53:03.890 --> 01:53:05.847
I can't get it unless I move.

1072
01:53:21.658 --> 01:53:24.231
This is it. This might be the right file.

1073
01:53:39.884 --> 01:53:41.462
- You got it!
- Yes!

1074
01:53:52.188 --> 01:53:53.219
What works?

1075
01:53:53.314 --> 01:53:56.019
All security systems are enabled.
We got it!

1076
01:54:05.910 --> 01:54:06.775
Grant.

1077
01:54:07.203 --> 01:54:10.120
Mr. Hammond. the phones are working.

1078
01:54:10.623 --> 01:54:13.458
<i>- The children all right?
- The children are fine.</i>

1079
01:54:13.835 --> 01:54:17.204
Call the mainland.
Tell 'em to send the damn helicopters.

1080
01:54:18.422 --> 01:54:20.047
It's gonna cut through the glass!

1081
01:55:14.645 --> 01:55:15.510
Move!

1082
01:57:18.935 --> 01:57:23.228
After careful consideration.
I've decided not to endorse your park.

1083
01:57:24.023 --> 01:57:25.221
So have I.

1084
01:57:26.305 --> 01:58:26.740
